---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
const title = "Classic Reverb";
---
<MainLayout title={title}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>Source: <a href="https://motu.com/products/motuaudio/ultralite-mk3/cuemix-fx-overview.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MOTU product page</a></p>

      <p>Classic Reverb™ is a DSP-powered hardware reverb built into the UltraLite-mk3. With decay lengths up to 60 seconds, it covers everything from tight room ambience to vast cathedrals — entirely in hardware, adding zero CPU load to the computer.</p>

      <h2>Parameters</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Room Type:</strong> selects the reverb character — room, hall, plate, chamber, etc. Each type has a distinct density and reflection pattern.</li>
        <li><strong>Size:</strong> scales the apparent room dimensions from a small booth to a large concert hall.</li>
        <li><strong>Pre-Delay:</strong> sets the time between the dry signal and the first reflection. Set pre-delay to <strong>20 ms or more</strong> to create a sense of space between the vocal and the reverb tail — keeps the initial attack clear.</li>
        <li><strong>Decay:</strong> how long the reverb tail sustains before fading. Short decay (0.5–1.5s) for vocals in a tracking mix; longer decay (2–4s) for pads and atmosphere.</li>
        <li><strong>Diffusion:</strong> controls the density of the reflections. High diffusion = smooth, washy reverb tail; low diffusion = discrete, audible early reflections.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Using as a Send Effect in CueMix FX</h2>
      <p>In the Mix tab, each channel has a Reverb Send knob. Instead of inserting the reverb directly on a single channel, use it as a parallel send — multiple inputs (SM58 vocal, Hydrasynth bus) can share the same reverb simultaneously while the dry signal remains unaffected. This is more flexible and CPU-efficient than per-channel inserts.</p>

      <h2>Vocalist Comfort Reverb</h2>
      <p>During tracking, send a small amount of the SM58 input to the Classic Reverb in the headphone cue mix. Singers perform better when they can hear a little reverb on their voice — it relaxes the delivery. Keep the reverb in the headphone mix only; record the dry signal to Ableton for clean production-side processing.</p>

      <figure>
        <img src="https://cdn-data.motu.com/site/images/cuemix-fx/mix_large.jpg" alt="CueMix FX software interface" />
        <figcaption>Classic Reverb is accessible in the CueMix FX Reverb tab.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
